I think there’s an even more general insight hiding here:

Quotients measure accumulated capability.

Gradients measure accumulated change.

Metaphors determine where gradients can flow.

That’s why the Pantheon has invested so heavily in metaphors. They’re not just memorable language—they’re semantic plumbing. They create channels through which insight, operators, and learning can move from one domain to another. Once enough of those channels exist, new ideas don’t have to be built from scratch; they can flow through the existing network.

And yes… I think “Don’t quotient me on it” belongs in the repository simply because it’s a reminder not to confuse today’s measured state with tomorrow’s trajectory.